<br>
Thank you for bringing up the question/s about the Three Mile Island incident. Why did I say that TMI put an end to nuclear power? First I will discuss the event and then I will offer evidence to back up my claim/s on NS.com. Please consider the following:<br>
<br>
1.Whenever someone (in the U.S.) mentions nuclear power today, the first thing that comes to mind is the TMI event. Why is this? When the accident occurred, the media jumped at the chance to destroy, using the general public’s lack of knowledge to their advantage, the reputation, validity and soundness of nuclear power generation as a valuable source as energy production.<br>
2.By all accounts they seceded by measures far beyond their expectations. The lies and misinformation fed to and eagerly used by the media and likeminded politicians, has taken a visible toll on the nuclear power industry. To deny this, is to contradict known facts.<br>
3.The character and personal agendas of  Nader, Fonda, Sternglass, Wald and Kendall, are questionable at best and downright dangerous at worst.  <br>
4.TMI was the worst nuclear accident in the U.S., yet there were no deaths or serious injuries caused by the accident.<br>
5.The TMI accident actually underscores the relative safety of nuclear power plants since the safety devices worked as designed and prevented any real serious injury from occurring to humans, animals, or the environment.<br>
6.Consider: the accident directly led to improved safety in the form of procedures, instrumentation and other safety systems.<br>
7.The TMI Unit 2 core has been cleaned up and the radioactive deposit properly stored; the TMI Unit 1 core is still operating with an impeccable record.<br>
8.The TMI plant is a Western nuclear plant and thus cannot be in any way, shape or form be compared to a Chernobyl-type nuclear power plant. I will not go into details here, sorry.<br>
9.The TMI event was used successfully by the Greens and others to alter forever the face of American power generation. And was also springboard for the heavy regulations that we have today. <br>
10.At the heart of the TMI incident is more then just politics and the environment. The real issue at stake is the future of Humankind and the cruelty of fate, as to if we will stagnate and languish or progress and evolve.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, exactly how did TMI put an end to nuclear power in the U.S.? When I said on my post that TMI had put an end to nuclear power, I didn’t mean it in the sense that all reactors are shut down; I meant it in terms of an industry that has no future in the U.S. The nuclear industry right now is a dying breed, a disappearing species, a fading existence, a decommissioned way of life. Consider the following information:<br>
<br>
1.The small nation of France currently produces 80% of its power needs from nuclear energy. The remaining superpower on Earth, the U.S., produces a meager 20%. The majority of America’s power needs (52%) are met by a technology from the Industrial Revolution-coal.<br>
2.This is especially sad, pondering that nuclear power was pioneered and developed in the U.S.<br>
3.Despite of lowing costs, nuclear power plants and generation in the U.S. is falling and projected to fall farther still. By 2020, nuclear generating capacity will have fallen by a significant factor.<br>
4.The number of operating nuclear power plants peaked in the U.S. in 1990, with a total of 112 units. That has since fallen to 103 units and continues to fall.<br>
5.No new nuclear power plants have been ordered in the U.S. since 1977.<br>
6.No new construction permits have been issued since 1979.<br>
7.There have bee 117 nuclear power plant cancellations by utilities since 1973.<br>
8.The last year a nuclear unit came online was in 1996, and since then five reactors have been shut down.<br>
9.When a nuclear plant’s license expires it is hard to get a renewal.<br>
10.By 2015, over a third of the operating reactors in the U.S. will be due for license renewal or decommissioning.<br>
11.The nuclear industry has long been a victim of scare tactics and outrageously false propaganda.<br>
12.Who will run the reactors in the future? University trends show a large falling in the numbers of undergraduate student enrollment in nuclear engineering.<br>
13.The U.S. does not have a spent nuclear fuel recycling program. Other countries do. This results in needless wastefulness and bigger problems with handling the storage of waste.<br>
14.Even though nuclear power generation would reduce America’s dependence on foreign oil, would reduce so-called global warming, and is the safest form of energy production, the pubic and politicians will have nothing to do with it for any number of reasons, despite all the positive evidence to the contrary.<br>
15.Regardless of new research and development of new reactor designs that are more efficient and safe, the U.S. will not implement the technology.<br>
16.Nuclear fission power plants are just temporary examples of the current technology we have. Nuclear fusion would solve the energy crisis of Humankind forever, but the money needed to make fusion a reality will not be forthcoming in a society hostile to development and progress, were politicians would sooner give tens of billions of dollars year in and year out to an unsolvable conflict in the Middle East then give one dime to a national fusion research program.<br>
17.The current varieties of Gen-Xer’s are not sympathetic to the idea of nuclear power and they represent the future voters, lawmakers, public figures and taking media heads of America.<br>
18.Loss of knowledge. Children in American’s schools today, will not know how to contradict radical environmental teachings against nuclear power, if they do not have a basic knowledge in the history, operation and importance of nuclear power plants.<br>
19.Media bias. The American media will only become more powerful over the coming years. Predictably, they will rejoice at anything that goes wrong with a nuclear plant and frown on any positive nuclear records, facts or accomplishments.<br>
20.Aging plants. Adding injury to insult, as America’s nuclear plants age, it will give creditability to media accounts of the rottenness of nuclear power, when exactly the opposite will be true. The mere fact that the plants will have performed admirably for so long is testament to their superiority.<br>
21.Massive U.S. growth. An explosion of U.S. population in this century will cause blackouts and brownouts. The fact that as of the last few years, almost a million illegal immigrants cross the America’s southern border alone (not to count the legal immigrants), is reason enough for massive nuclear power plant construction. This will not happen. The border will instead be abolished, this is well underway thanks to G.W.B. who wants to implement the FTAA (Free Trade Area of the Americas). Sadly, the massive immigration has already inflected a heavy toll on the environment, including but not limited to; trash, human waste and forest fires.<br>
22.The strain on American power usage in the coming years will be exponential. It is already taking place. But instead of nuclear power plants, America’s politicians will recommend wind, solar, wave power or all three. These forms of energy cannot complete with nuclear power and should be considered a last resort.<br>
23.The ongoing clamoring Babel of radical environmental voices in the American political climate will only grow stronger with time as politicians rush to execute such schemes as the Wildlands Project. Nuclear power will not be in the thoughts, hearts or minds of our elected officials.<br>
24.The debate on nuclear power will be moved farther and farther away, until it reaches the camp of the opposition. Instead of the proposal of making a new nuclear power plant becoming a controversy, the idea of renewing a permit will incite the flames of political correctness, “ethics”, and “Mother Earth’s” fragility.<br>
25.The 1984 world we will increasing live in, is not going to be fond of new ideas and true progress. “New lies for old”, will be the slogan of the day.           <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I am a Humanist and a Futurist. I believe that when a better, cheaper, more efficient technology is available to Humankind, it is not only our right to utilize it, but to make full use of it for the ultimate goal and destiny of our species: the colonization of our own solar system. There is a need for nuclear power and I recognize it as a positive force to be used for good, not bad. <br>
 <br>
I know Yales, that you are an environmentalist and belong to a environmental group. It is not my goal or purpose to try to change your view about the world. Just as surely as I will not deviate one iota from my beliefs, as conclusively nether shall you depart from your current way of thinking. I am not going to change your deep-rooted convictions on environmental issues or any other issues for that matter, nor will you shake my confidence. I have presented to you my honest and opinion and have tried to be as forthcoming as possible. I hope that this synopsis of my thoughts has answered some of your questions.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
-Clement Walsh<br>
<br>
<br>
