<br>
Lets look at the facts to determine TMI's role in the collapse of atomic power in the US:<br>
 (please admire the charts I made in Freelance)<br>
==============================================<br>
<br>
A) Did the 1979 TMI accident cause the utilities to stop buying reactors?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/1953orders.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
-- Key FACT: Orders had ALREADY fallen to ZERO prior to the accident<br>
<br>
==============================================<br>
<br>
B) Did the 1979 TMI accident cause the utilities to CANCEL existing orders for reactors?<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/1953cancel.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
-- Key FACT: Roughly the same number cancelled BEFORE the accident and AFTER. <br>
<br>
No TMI effect.<br>
<br>
==============================================<br>
<br>
C) Did the 1979 TMI accident prevent reactors from being finished and started-up? <br>
<br>
After a 1 year pause to study the accident, we see:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/1953starts.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
-- Key FACT: After a brief pause by the NRC, reactors again came online, business-as-usual<br>
<br>
==============================================<br>
<br>
D) Did the 1979 TMI accident cause the utilities to end the growth in nuclear capacity?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/1953total.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
-- Key FACT: With no appreciable break after TMI, capacity rose for many year, till it started its long fade-out.<br>
<br>
==============================================<br>
<br>
Thus we see that any &quot;TMI effect&quot; is illusionary.<br>
